<img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-1685199 lazyload lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-1.png" alt="" width="1280" height="1742" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-1.png 958w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-1-439x598.jpg 439w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-1-846x1152.jpg 846w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-1-176x240.jpg 176w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-1-353x480.jpg 353w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-1-441x600.jpg 441w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" /> Nigerian multi-hyphenate Cruel Santino (fka Santi) has released his sophomore album, Subaru Boys : FINAL HEAVEN (out on Monster Boy/Interscope Records). A 21-track conceptual album (co-produced by Cruel Santino), the project is broken up into multiple arcs, each with its own theme and navigator, guiding the listener through a sonic tale of war and glory. Joining Cruel Santino on this epic adventure are the project’s special guests including Skepta, Amaarae, Koffee, Gus Dapperton and a slew of new music darlings from the auteurial “Subaru” world. Written across continents, the first half of the project squarely taps into the Alté and Afrobeats lane (with songs like “Matilda” and “Swagger Back”), Cruel also lends himself to sample from recent Grime resurgence on “The Pearls.” While the latter half is influenced by more modern genres heard on “Fallin” (which leans R&B) and “Beautiful Nothing” (draws from bedroom pop sounds with a little help from collaborator Gus Dapperton). Gliding through genres and musical inspirations, Cruel taps into many references to create a body of work that is both cohesive and aims to please many listeners. Subaru Boys : FINAL HEAVEN was released on Monster Boy — a joint venture deal that Cruel Santino announced with Interscope Records in 2020. He is the first Nigerian artist ever to strike a JV deal with a major record label. See the full tracklist HERE: <img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-1685201 lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed.png" alt="" width="1280" height="1274" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed.png 894w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-601x598.jpg 601w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-58x58.jpg 58w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-116x116.jpg 116w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-100x100.jpg 100w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-200x200.jpg 200w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-241x240.jpg 241w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-482x480.jpg 482w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/unnamed-600x597.jpg 600w" sizes="(max-width: 1280px) 100vw, 1280px" /> Subaru Boys : FINAL HEAVEN Tracklisting: Double Vengeance 1.  Matilda feat. Brazy 2. I told Gus I’m Dreamin 3. War In The Trenches 4. Tapenga 5. The Pearls feat. Maison2500 Mermaid Aqua 6. Heating Rocks 7. Mermaid Aqua Subaru Girl Unlimited Special 8. Own Game feat. Bratzbih, EBEE & Seo Final Champion 9. Deadman Bone feat. Koffee 10. Final Champion 11. Swagger Back feat. WifiGawd 12. Subaru Boys OST (Interlude) First Heaven 13. First Heaven 14. Beautiful Nothing feat. Gus Dapperton 15. Born Again feat. Amaarae 16. Wickey City feat. Gus Dapperton 17. Fallin feat. Chi Virgo and Solis 18. Way of The Serpent 19. Sucre / Saga Ship 20. Dirty Eyes, Evil Manners feat. Skepta 21. Sa-Karuchan